{
  "texts": [
    "More generally, we will see in Section 4 a general assumption that characterizes the best possible learning rate in classification problems.",
    "And as a special case, the noiseless case indeed leads to rates in 1/n.",
    "Let us summarize the important take home message from Theorem 3.3:",
    "• the empirical PAC-Bayes bounds seen so far were in 1/ √ n,",
    "• in the noiseless case E θ∼ρ [r(θ)] = 0, it is possible to have a bound in 1/n, on the condition that one uses the right PAC-Bayes inequality, for example Theorem 3.3 or Theorem 3.2."
  ]
}